CGRS Privacy Policy

This privacy policy (the “Privacy Policy”) discloses the privacy practices of the Center for Gender and Refugee Studies (“CGRS,” “we” or “us”) based at the University of California College of Law, San Francisco (“UC Law SF”) and uses of the information that we gather about users (“End Users”) and expert witnesses for asylum and other humanitarian matters, including clinics or other organizations that provide expert evaluations (“Experts”, and together with End Users, collectively, “Users,” a “User” or “you”) via https://cgrs.uclawsf.edu and any related applications, services, tools and features, including CGRS’s Expert Witness Database (as defined below), Technical Assistance Library, the Expert Witness Resource Library as well as submissions by you to CGRS (collectively, the “Services”). Note that this Privacy Policy does not apply to the general website for UC Law SF (www.uclawsf.edu) or the websites of any of UC Law SF’s other centers or departments. By using the Services you agree to the collection, use and disclosure of your information as described in this Privacy Policy.

The Services can only be accessed and used subject to the CGRS Terms of Use. Please read this Privacy Policy carefully. By accessing, downloading, or using any of the Services, you agree to the use of your information as described in this Privacy Policy. If you do not agree to this Privacy Policy, you may not access and use the Services.

MODIFICATIONS OF PRIVACY POLICY

We may periodically modify the Privacy Policy. If we make material changes to the Privacy Policy we will use reasonable efforts to notify you via the Services (e.g., by posting a notice on our website indicating that the Privacy Policy has been changed) and take such other steps as required by applicable law. If you do not agree with any modifications to the Privacy Policy, please do not access or continue to use the Services.

COLLECTION AND USE OF INFORMATION

When you access or use the Services, CGRS collects information about you in various ways, including through your submissions to the Services, participation in the Services and registration for the Services and through certain third-party service providers. CGRS collects the following information:

The following information about all Users who make an account: name, phone number, e-mail address, username, password, government affiliation, profession and organization. If you choose to use the Services and register an account, you are responsible for keeping your account credentials safe. Do not share your username, password or other access details with anyone else, except that Expert Witness users may authorize third parties to maintain their profiles as specifically provided for on the Expert Witness registration form. If you believe your account has been compromised, please contact us immediately.

The following information from Users who register on the Services specifically as an asylum seeker, an attorney or an Expert: name, email address, phone number, password and organization.

The following information about Experts who create a profile on our database where Users can locate and engage Experts (“Expert Witness Database”): name, preferred pronouns, title, email address, physical address, company, type of expert, related websites, institutional affiliations, educational background and other academic qualifications, information included in a CV, topic(s) of expertise (e.g., child psychology, gender-based violence, gang violence, violence against children), countries of expertise, language ability, fee structure, willingness to testify in court, availability for engagement, prior declarations and any references to the Expert in court decisions.

The following payment information from Users who choose to make a donation: name, email, partial credit card information and billing address, which is stored on Administrative Service Providers platforms.

The following information from Users who submit an asylum case intake form: client information (e.g., country of origin, date of border crossing, indigent status, gender, age, minor unaccompanied status, details of persecution), organization information (e.g., sources of funding), case information (e.g., qualification for legal services programs, procedural details, decision status, case issues, case summary, filing deadlines, participating attorneys).

The following information from Users who submit an outcomes form based on a prior case decision: the date of the decision and relevant decisionmaker (i.e., asylum office, immigration judge, etc.), applicant information (e.g., age, detention status at the time of the decision, any related applicants, whether the applicant had representation, and if so, who applicant represented by), protected grounds considered by the adjudicator, information regarding the reasoning for the outcome, whether the case is subject to the Asylum Processing Rule, whether the applicant has been granted other forms of relief, and information about the Expert in the case, if any, (e.g., name, type of expert, whether the expert’s qualifications or findings were challenged, whether the court mentioned the expert or their testimony in its decision) and any additional information or documents you choose to include in the form.

The following information from survey participants: name, email address, phone number, law firm and any feedback on the relevant Services which the survey participant chooses to provide.

Any other information that you choose to include in communications with us.

SUBMISSION OF DOCUMENTS, REVIEWS AND COMMENTS

We collect information that you voluntarily provide as part of the Services, including messages, documents (including court documents or other documents related to cases), reviews, and other materials related to asylum matters or court proceedings which you submit through the Services (“User Generated Content”). CGRS or others may store, share, display, reproduce, publish, or otherwise use your User Generated Content and may or may not attribute it to you. With respect to any User Generated Content submitted by Users requesting assistance with an asylum case, CGRS may use such User Generated Content to (i) provide tailored assistance and materials for your case, (ii) inform our analyses of treatment of gender-based, child, LGBTQ and other claims for national policy and advocacy and (iii) share such User Generated Content with attorneys who seek our assistance in analogous cases or organizations to support our mutual advocacy efforts.

If you do not want certain information shared with others, you should not submit such User Generated Content to the Services. Once you have submitted User Generated Content, we reserve the right to publish it in any medium to others, and it may become public and able to be shared with third parties.

Please note that we do not control who will have access to the information that you choose to make available to others, and cannot ensure that parties who have access to such information will respect your privacy or keep it secure. We are not responsible for the privacy or security of any information that you make publicly available on the features permitting creation of User Generated Content or what others do with information you share with them on such platforms. We are not responsible for the accuracy, use or misuse of any User Generated Content that you disclose or receive from third parties through email lists.

